<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Haekkerup: UN Radar Stations Installed in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Haekkerup: UN Radar Stations Installed in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2206104794 Paris AFP in English 1019 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2206104794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Copenhagen, June 22 (AFP) -- The United Nations has 
installed radar stations in Bosnia-Herzegovina in order to 
pinpoint assailants, the Danish defence minister said Wednesday 
[22 June]. 
  Hans Haekkerup said in a written reply to parliament's 
Defence Committee that "these radars were set up in Tuzla, 
Sarajevo, Bihac and Mostar, after Tuzla airport was shelled on 
May 17." 
  At the time, Denmark had complained that the UN Protection 
Force [UNPROFOR] had not responded to requests for air support 
by the Danish contingent, which was being attacked, had made. 
  The radars, which have a 30 kilometre (19 mile) range with 
20 
metre (66 foot) accuracy, can pinpoint the location of guns and 
canon and thereby enable the United Nations to riposte. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

