<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman on U.S. Military Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Spokesman on U.S. Military Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2206151294 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1445 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2206151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, June 22 (AA) -- Foreign Ministry Spokesman 
Ferhat Ataman said today that Turkey was to continue initiatives 
and efforts so that U.S. aid is given in line with Turkey's 
views. 
  Ataman told his weekly press conference that Turkey would 
not 
accept the linking of the U.S. aid to any precondition. 
  He also recalled that the House Appropriations Committee has 
not approved the proposal passed by the House of Representatives 
to suspend 25 percent of the aid to Turkey. 
  `In return the Senate committee decided to include a clause 
in the text under which U.S. military material sold and 
transferred to Turkey will not be used by Turkey for domestic 
security and police purposes,' he said. 
  Ataman said that that decision was to be put before the 
Senate. 
  `Since there is a difference between the text of the House 
and the Senate, the committee has to review the issue,' Ataman 
said. 
  `If the committee agrees on a conciliating text, this will 
then be voted separately in the general assembly of the Senate 
and the House and submitted to the approval of the president,' 
Ataman said. 
  `However, if a conciliation is not reached,' he said, `it 
was 
likely that the previous practices on extending aid to Turkey 
might prevail.' 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

