<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spain Offers Logistic Support </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spain Offers Logistic Support </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206154694 Madrid RNE International in Spanish 1300 GMT 22 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2206154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE International </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] In statements made to this radio station 
Javier Solana, Spanish foreign minister, said Spain was willing 
to contribute to the logistics of the French intervention in 
Rwanda as soon as the UN Security Council has given the go-ahead 
for this military operation. Javier Solana. 
  [Begin Solana recording] Here is the latest information. 
This morning -- local time in New York -- the UN Security 
Council will pass a resolution allowing a multinational force to 
distribute humanitarian aid along the Rwandan borders to Rwandan 
citizens who are being expelled. It will not be deployed in 
Rwanda. 
  Spain's role: Spain will vote in favor of this Security 
Council resolution. It not only supports this resolution, Spain 
was the first country to suggest that such an initiative had to 
be taken. 
  Secondly, what kind of aid are we going to contribute? Spain 
will not deploy armed forces in the field. We will lend 
logistical support to the whole operation which will be run by 
the French. The French already have troops deployed in Africa 
and they will be in charge of the operation. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] Up until now the French have received support 
from the members of the Western European Union meeting today in 
Brussels. 

</TEXT>

