<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "European Union: Italian Agenda for </F>
Corfu Summit"] 
  [Excerpt] (ANSA) Rome, June 22 -- Italy will try to delay 
the election of a new European Commission president and will 
raise objections to financing proposed for the so-called Delors 
Plan on jobs at the summit of EU [European Union] leaders in 
Corfu, Greece, this weekend, Foreign Undersecretary Livio Caputo 
told reporters Wednesday [22 June]. 
  On the election of a new EU executive chief, to replace 
resigning president Jacques Delors, Italy will ask that a 
special summit be called in September because a unanimous 
decision "is impossible today" and forcing a decision at the 
Greek summit may cause rifts within the Union. 
  Germany and France have endorsed Belgian Prime Minister 
Jean-Luc Dehaene but Italian Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi 
seems undecided between Dehaene and Dutch Prime Minister Ruud 
Lubbers. Two other candidates are also in the running for the 
Commission presidency. 
  The two top items on the agenda at Corfu June 24 and 25 are 
the signing of a cooperation accord with Russia and the signing 
of membership treaties with Austria, Finland, Sweden and Norway, 
which would join the Union in January 1995 if the governments of 
all 12 member states ratify the treaties in time. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

