<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Italy Unhappy With Milk Quota </F>
Compromise"] 
  [Excerpt] (ANSA) Luxembourg, June 21 -- Italy is not 
satisfied with a European Union [EU] compromise document which 
fixes milk quotas and farm prices for the coming season, an 
Italian spokesman said as EU farm ministers met here Tuesday [21 
June] for the second day of their price marathon. 
  "There is confirmation of Italy's production quotas for 
milk, 
but we are not satisfied with proposals on milk derivatives, 
citrus fruit, tobacco, olive oil, beef and rice," said the 
spokesman. 
  In an interview this morning with the Euronews TV channel, 
Italy's Agriculture Minister Adriana Poli Bortone said "there is 
a 50 percent chance that the issue will be brought up at the 
Corfu European Council summit." 
  Italy has threatened to bring the issue up at the summit 
should its demands not be met in the Luxembourg marathon. 
Complicating today's talks, however, is a Greek demand to 
triple its milk quota to 300,000 tonnes a year. The compromise 
document approves Italy's request to hike its quota from nine 
million tonnes to 9.9 million tonnes per year. 
  "We don't want to be perpetually subjected to the blackmail 
of the milk quotas," Poli Bortone told her colleagues here. 
"Italy has recognised the mistakes it made on the quotas, and 
now it does not want to be judged for a sort of original sin," 
she said. 
  The minister described the situation as "unsustainable" 
given 
that Italy is only 60 percent self-sufficient in milk and 
imports around 9 million metric tons each year. 
  Poli Bortone pointed out that "our requests on future prices 
and measures to manage markets are all zero-cost," regarding 
tobacco, rice, olive oil, beef, citrus fruits, and the famous 
cheeses of the Po valley like parmigiano and grana. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

