<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   CDU/CSU Leaders Urge SPD To Dissociate From PDS </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CDU/CSU Leaders Urge SPD To Dissociate From PDS </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2106170794 Hamburg DPA in German 1435 GMT 21 Jun 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2106170794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Weimar (DPA) -- The Bundestag Group chairmen of the 
Christian Democratic Union [CDU] and the Christian Social Union 
[CSU] have called on the Social Democratic Party of Germany 
[SPD] federal party congress in Halle "to dissociate itself 
clearly from cooperation with the Party of Democratic Socialism 
[PDS] at all levels." In a statement by the Bundestag Group 
Chairmen's Conference in Weimar on Tuesday [21 June], the 
successor organization of the Socialist Unity Party of Germany 
[SED] is called extreme-left and a danger to democracy. The 
chiefs of the CDU and CSU groups demanded that political action 
be taken against the PDS with all democratic means. 
  The declaration, which was unanimously adopted in Weimar, 
says that the PDS has to be combated in the same way as the 
extreme-right Republikaner. The SPD is particularly requested 
to do this. "It is part of the SPD's historical omissions that 
it does not dissociate itself from extreme-left forces clearly 
enough." The SPD merger with the Communist Party of Germany 
into the SED in eastern Germany in April 1946 had disastrous 
consequences for many upright Social Democrats, it was stated. 

</TEXT>

