<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Constitutional Reform `Questionable' Before Election </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Constitutional Reform `Questionable' Before Election </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2106155794 Hamburg DPA in German 1140 GMT 21 Jun 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2106155794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- Because of opposition opinions within 
the coalition, it has become questionable whether the 
constitutional reform that has been prepared in years of work 
will actually be passed before the Bundestag election. This 
became clear on Tuesday [21 June], following the coalition 
meeting chaired by Chancellor Helmut Kohl. The second and third 
reading of a reform package to amend the Basic Law was scheduled 
for next Thursday in the Berlin Reichstag. 
  As has been learned, there are disagreements between the 
Christian Democratic Union /Christian Social Union [CDU/CSU] and 
the Free Democratic Party [FDP] in particular about the 
expansion of powers for the laender. There is also disagreement 
about the acceptance of minority protection and equal rights for 
married and unmarried couples as well as the current form of 
animal protection. On the other hand, there is no dispute about 
including the protection for handicapped people in the 
constitution. 
  According to CDU/CSU circles, the FDP is calling for an 
entire package of measures and opposes adopting those individual 
points that are not disputed between the coalition parties. 
This makes the situation difficult, the CDU/CSU group leaders 
said. From the CSU, it was heard that under these circumstances 
it might become difficult to achieve a decision at the Berlin 
Bundestag session next week. The strengthening of the laenders' 
rights, which they want, might be postponed to the next 
legislative period. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

