<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Martino Notes Conditions for Sending Troops to Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Martino Notes Conditions for Sending Troops to Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2206140194 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1251 GMT 22 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2206140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Rwanda: Martino on Conditions for </F>
Sending Troops"] 
  [Excerpt] (ANSA) Rome, June 22 -- Italian Foreign Minister 
Antonio Martino, speaking during a break in a Senate Foreign 
Affairs Committee hearing this morning, specified the conditions 
under which this country would consider sending troops to an 
international peace force to Rwanda. 
  The United Nations would have to vote a request for peace 
keeping forces under the command of the Western European Union 
[WEU] or of NATO, Martino said. And to guarantee that force's 
effectiveness, it would have to be based on an accord among the 
national forces being deployed, the Foreign Minister added. 
  "Under those conditions we may even consider sending troops, 
but if those conditions do not hold, we will end up with a 
unilateral initiative," Martino added. 
  The decision taken Monday [20 June] by the WEU in Brussels 
to 
send French troops backed by "logistical support" on the part of 
Great Britain, Holland, Belgium and Luxembourg "is a move in the 
right direction," the Foreign Minister said. 
  "It involves international coordination, which gives us the 
guarantee this is not a unilateral initiative but a multilateral 
effort that puts the emphasis on the humanitarian aspect of the 
mission," he told reporters, adding he thought it was possible 
the WEU-sponsored mission "could put an end to the massacres." 
  "What we were worried about was a unilateral move that would 
have had a neocolonialist flavor and would have aggravated 
rather than reduced tensions." 
  The Italian government had urged the broadest possible 
participation among WEU nations. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

