<H3> <TI>   Government Implements Trade Embargo Against Haiti </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Implements Trade Embargo Against Haiti </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2306134994 Bern ATSA/SDAA Database in French 1059 GMT 23 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2306134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA Database </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed VF/JR: "Bern Adheres to the UN Sanctions </F>
Against Haiti -- Switzerland Will Enforce an Extensive Trade 
Embargo"] 
  [Excerpt] Bern, 23 Jun (ATS) -- Bern has decided to 
implement the new UN sanctions against Haiti that entered into 
force on 22 May. The federal counselor approved an extensive 
trade embargo and restrictions in the field of air and maritime 
transportation. These measures add up to those already taken by 
Switzerland on 30 June 1993. They enter into force on Thursday 
[23 June]. 
  In addition, the individuals who took part in the 1991 coup 
d'etat as well as their relatives will not be allowed to enter 
Switzerland until further notice. This restriction also applies 
to the members of the government in power since 1991 and to the 
members of the Haitian police and Armed Forces. In a joint 
communique released on Thursday, the Federal Department of 
Foreign Affairs and the Federal Department of Public Economy 
announced that a visa would be mandatory for the holders of 
diplomatic or special passports. 
  The Swiss trade embargo against Haiti now applies to all 
imports and exports between Switzerland and Haiti. However, 
medicines, food stuffs, and publications such as newspapers, 
periodicals, or books are excluded. Bern has been banning the 
sale or the export of weapons, oil, and oil products for one 
year already. 
  Swiss ships are no longer allowed to navigate in Haitian 
waters and the use of the Swiss or Haitian airspace by aircraft 
[not specified] is prohibited. This measure does not apply to 
international flights. The freeze on the funds and capital 
goods of the junta in power is extended. This measure also 
applies to the assets of individuals who are under the direct or 
indirect control of the military government. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

