<H3> <TI>   Kinkel for Majority Voting in EU Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel for Majority Voting in EU Foreign Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206134894 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1133 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel 
intends during the German presidency of the European Union [EU] 
gradually to achieve majority decisionmaking in foreign and 
security policy. Speaking to the press in Bonn today, Kinkel 
also called for the "interlocking" of the EU with the Western 
European Union (WEU) defense alliance to be pushed forward. A 
common European foreign policy is particularly necessary in view 
of the events in former Yugoslavia, Kinkel said. 
  Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt (Free Democratic Party of 
Germany) criticized the European Commission's white paper at the 
news conference, saying that "a series of interventionist 
principles" can be identified in it. Rexrodt argued by contrast 
for private initiative to be given priority over state activity. 

</TEXT>

