<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paris To Fund Humanitarian Radio in Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paris To Fund Humanitarian Radio in Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2206120794 Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS in French 21 Jun 94 
p 15 </F>

<F P=103> BR2206120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "France To Fund `Humanitarian Radio'"] </F>
  [Text] France will fund half of the budget (in other words 
250,000 francs out of 500,000 francs) for a "humanitarian radio 
for Rwanda," which will be set up shortly by Reporters Without 
Borders, the journalists' rights defense organization, Lucette 
Michaux-Chevry, the minister-delegate for humanitarian action, 
announced yesterday. 
  "This radio will provide a useful counterbalance to the 
`Mille Collines [one thousand hills] Radio,' whose devastating 
influence is well-known," the minister said in a communique, 
referring to the radio controlled by the Hutu extremists and its 
calls for violence. According to Mrs. Michaux-Chevry, this 
radio, "serving nongovernmental organizations," could provide a 
valuable service, for instance by broadcasting information about 
displaced persons, those who have disappeared or are being 
sought, advice on travel, security, access to medicines, 
drinking water, and so forth. 

</TEXT>

