<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rail Strike `Seriously' Disrupts Services </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rail Strike `Seriously' Disrupts Services </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2206122794 Paris AFP in English 1126 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2206122794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, June 22 (AFP) -- French rail workers 
protesting job cuts went on strike on Wednesday [22 June], 
seriously disrupting train services across most of the country. 
  High-speed trains serving the south and west of the country 
were hit, with one train in three running between Paris, Lyon 
and Marseille, and one train in two working Atlantic routes. 
  But the high-speed service linking Paris with Lille in the 
north was not affected. 
  Regular mainline services were also severely hit in the 
western, south-western and south-eastern regions, but operated 
normally in the north and east. Suburban Paris services were cut 
by a third or a half. 
  Railway workers are protesting plans by the state-owned SNCF 
rail company to cut 5,900 jobs in 1994, after doing away with 
6,000 jobs in the previous year. The strikers, who began their 
action Tuesday night, go back to work on Thursday morning. 

</TEXT>

