<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Commander on Russian Military Build-Up in North </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Commander on Russian Military Build-Up in North </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206202194 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1600 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2206202194 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Finnish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to Admiral Jan Klenberg, commander in 
chief of the defense forces, the implementation of disarmament 
agreements between the superpowers is causing a military 
build-up in northern Europe. Russia is transferring more troops 
to areas near Finland because of the Conventional Forces in 
Europe Treaty, and the implementation of Start II is making the 
Northern Fleet the most important nuclear weapons center for 
Russia. 
  Klenberg was explaining the military development of the 
Calotte area in Rovaniemi today. Klenberg said that there are 
no changes in the military situation in northern Europe despite 
the upheavals in Central Europe. 
  Klenberg also reiterated the defense forces' negative stance 
toward new road and railway connections to areas that are 
important from the military point of view. However, the 
Ministry of Communications is continuing to plan the Salla 
[northeastern Finland] railway line. Experts evaluating the 
profitability of the Salla railway line have recommended that 
one-third of the financing come from share capital and long-term 
transport agreements. The rest would be financed with loans 
from the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development. The 
Ministry of Communications is to have talks on the project with 
the Russians at a ministerial meeting planned for the autumn. 

</TEXT>

