<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Official Leaves for Pipeline Talks in Iraq </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Official Leaves for Pipeline Talks in Iraq </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2206164694 Ankara ANATOLIA in Turkish 1515 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2206164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara (AA) -- Foreign Ministry Under Secretary 
Ozdem Sanberk left Ankara today for Baghdad to conduct contacts 
on the Karkuk-Yumurtalik oil pipeline. 
  Tomorrow, Ambassador Sanberk will proceed by land from Amman 
to Baghdad, where he will meet with Iraqi Foreign Ministry Under 
Secretary al-Qaysi. [name as received] 
  In his news conference today, Foreign Ministry Spokesman 
Ferhat Ataman announced that Sanberk is also expected to meet 
with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq 'Aziz and other 
government officials. 
  Recalling that Sanberk previously held contacts on the 
subject in Paris, Washington, and New York, Ataman remarked that 
these meetings focused on resolving the issue at the UN Security 
Council with a technical resolution. 
  Ataman noted that Sanberk will brief and exchange views with 
the Iraqis on the elements of such a resolution. 
  Pointing out that Turkey has not received any official 
information with regard to Iraq's stand on the matter, Ataman 
said: 
  "We hope that the oil pipeline, which constitutes a valuable 
and important investment, will be salvaged, and a humanitarian 
contribution will consequently be made to the Iraqi people 
within the framework of the United Nations." 

</TEXT>

