<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Clarifies Mission of CSCE in Erzurum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Clarifies Mission of CSCE in Erzurum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2206174594 Ankara TURKISH DAILY NEWS in English 20 Jun 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> NC2206174594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TURKISH DAILY NEWS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara--The establishment of a base for Conference 
on Security and Cooperation in Europe (CSCE) observers to 
Nagorno-Karabakh is in no way similar in mandate or structure to 
Provide Comfort II, an allied force stationed in Turkey to 
protect Kurds in northern Iraq, a high-level Turkish official 
said Sunday [19 June]. Riza Turmen, the Foreign Ministry 
director responsible for ties with the CSCE, told reporters that 
the "base" in Erzurum would serve as a supply center for the 
CSCE observers who would be placed in the region to supervise a 
cease-fire between Armenians and Azeris. 
  The base in Erzurun would have a staff of 10 civilians, 
Turmen said. 
  Turmen also said that the first group of 34 people was 
planned to be sent to the Caucasus as soon as a cease-fire was 
established. Two weeks later, another 64 would be dispatched and 
the number of CSCE observers would be increased to 350. Four 
Turks will also be participating in the CSCE mission, Turmen 
said. 
  The mandate of the mission will be to supervise the 
cease-fire as well as the return of refugees. 
  "This large group will need back-up facilities, and Erzurun 
was selected to be the suitable spot for such a base," he said. 
Various press reports have called the CSCE operation a "Poised 
Hammer for the Armenians," drawing parallels between the Erzurum 
base and the allied force stationed in the Southeast to deter 
Baghdad from attacking the Kurds. The Foreign Ministry has 
categorically denied any similarities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-43958 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu121_q_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-121 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

