<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Rejects Amnesty International Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Rejects Amnesty International Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2206165494 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1530 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2206165494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, June 22 (AA) -- Foreign Ministry Spokesman 
Ferhat Ataman said today that the Amnesty International report 
showed once more that it has mistaken on the situation of human 
rights practices in Turkey. 
  Ataman told his weekly press conference that the image which 
the organization attempted to portray about Turkey did not 
reflect the facts. 
  Ataman said that parliament, independent justice, and a free 
press were functioning in Turkey which has been a member of the 
democratic Western community for half a century. 
  `It is a fact that the significant fall of terrorism leads 
to 
significant improvements in human rights practices,' he said. 
  Ataman also recalled that Article 8 of the antiterror law, 
which was criticized by Amnesty, was at present discussed at 
parliamentary commissions. 
  `Turkey is a transparent democracy. Anyone may visit any 
place, like a recent visit by Western ambassadors to the 
southeast,' he said. 
  In an annual report, the human rights group singled out 
Colombia and Turkey as being particularly aggressive violators 
and said they appear to be using U.S. military aid for torture, 
military attacks on civilians and other abuses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-43959 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu121_q_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-121 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   FYROM Agriculture Minister Arrives for Cooperation Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FYROM Agriculture Minister Arrives for Cooperation Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1506070594 Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network in Turkish 
2000 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1506070594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Eftim Ancev, agriculture, forestry, and water 
management minister of Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic 
of Macedonia -- FYROM], arrived in Turkey today on an official 
visit. The visiting minister and his delegation were received at 
Ankara's Esenboga Airport by Refaiddin Sahin, agriculture and 
village affairs minister. 
  In a statement at the airport, Sahin said Turkey attaches 
special importance to relations with Macedonia and is exerting 
efforts to develop these relations. Agricultural cooperation and 
assistance will be discussed during the visit, Sahin reported, 
adding that a scientific, economic, and technical cooperation 
protocol will be signed in the field of agriculture. 
  Ancev, in turn, expressed pleasure over visiting Turkey. He 
declared that Turkey's support is extremely important in the 
face of the Greek embargo on his country. 

</TEXT>

