<H3> <TI>   Russian Foreign Minister Signs NATO Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Foreign Minister Signs NATO Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2206110794 Brussels BELGA Database in French 0935 GMT 22 
Jun 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2206110794 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA Database </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed GGD: "Russia Joins PFP"] </F>
  [Text] Brussels, 22 Jun (BELGA) -- Russia officially signed 
the Partnership for Peace program [PFP], which provides for 
closer cooperation with NATO, on Wednesday [22 June]. 
  Russian Foreign Minister Kozyrev signed the PFP, 
implementing 
the NATO-Russia cooperation agreement, mainly in the military 
sphere, which the alliance proposed to other European countries 
and especially to its former Cold War enemies. 
  Addressing the ambassadors of NATO's 16 member countries at 
the alliance's Brussels Headquarters, the Russian foreign 
minister stated that "the preparation of an important 
Russian-NATO cooperation program has been launched. We have 
agreed on a large and profound dialogue as well as cooperation 
on issues in which Russia could make a substantial and unique 
contribution, corresponding to its importance and its 
responsibilities as major nuclear power in Europe and in the 
world." U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher attended the 
signing ceremony. 

</TEXT>

