<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Leaders Discuss Summit, Consider Delors Replacement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Leaders Discuss Summit, Consider Delors Replacement </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Christian Democrats Meet 22 Jun </H4>

<F P=102> AU2206185294 Hamburg DPA in German 1602 GMT 22 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2206185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels (DPA) -- The heads of government and party 
chairmen of the christian democratic parties in the European 
Union [EU] are meeting in Brussels on 22 June to coordinate 
policy for the forthcoming EU summit. 
  Their talks will be focused on a successor to European 
Commission Chairman Jacques Delors. The two most promising 
candidates for the top office, which will be vacant in January 
1995 -- Belgian Premier Jean-Luc Dehaene and Netherlands head of 
government Ruud Lubbers, both of them Christian democrats --will 
take part in the meeting, as will Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl. 
  Observers are hoping for a preliminary decision by the 
Christian democrats, which form the European People's Party 
group in the European Parliament. The socialist Jacques Delors 
will have a Christian democratic successor, who will be selected 
by the EU heads of state and government at their summit meeting 
on the Greek island of Corfu on 24 and 25 June. 
  Kohl's preferred candidate is Dehaene, who is apparently 
backed by the majority of the "Twelve." If the leadership of 
the European People's Party opts for one of the candidates, this 
vote will be decisive for the EU summit. The possibility has 
not been ruled out, however, that no vote will be taken, in 
order to avoid a conflict. Both candidates are considered 
"highly qualified" for the top position at EU headquarters. 
  The European People's Party leaders will also discuss the 
outcome of the EU parliamentary elections. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

