<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police To Go to Mostar; Civilian Status Stressed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police To Go to Mostar; Civilian Status Stressed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206150694 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1335 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- The German cabinet today approved 
sending 70 German police officers to the town of Mostar, which 
was destroyed in the civil war in Bosnia-Herzegovina. According 
to government spokesman Dieter Vogel, the police will take part 
in a civilian operation by the Western European Union [WEU], 
which is also to be supported by the administrative authorities 
in Mostar. 
  The WEU police contingent will be made up of a total of 200 
police officers. The cabinet approved Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel's view that a stronger international police element was 
necessary for the success of the European Union [EU]-appointed 
administrator, SPD [Social Democratic Party] politician Hans 
Koschnick, Vogel said. 
  The precondition for the start of the EU's administration in 
Mostar and sending the police was the complete demilitarization 
of the town under the supervision of the UN Protection Force, 
Vogel said. The police would only work "in safe surroundings." 
If the security situation did not meet the strict requirements 
of the EU, then the administration would be suspended and the 
personnel withdrawn. 
  Germany will make 50 new 20-tonne low-loaders available to 
the United Nations for "urgently required" heavy goods transport 
in war-torn Yugoslavia. The United Nations will also be given 
16 German experts to deal with the opening and starting up of 
the airport in Tuzla. The German Government is also willing to 
get involved in aid flights with Bundeswehr aircraft once the 
airport is open. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

