<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   To Meet With Kliridhis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    To Meet With Kliridhis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2206150594 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2206150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Government spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis announced 
today that Joe Clark, the UN secretary general's special 
representative on Cyprus, will arrive on the island at 1730 this 
afternoon and at 2000 will be received by President Glavkos 
Kliridhis. The spokesman also said that UN Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali had a telephone conversation with President 
Kliridhis last night and announced his intention to send Clark 
to Cyprus. Kliridhis, the spokesman added, asked Butrus-Ghali 
whether Clark would be carrying any letter. Butrus-Ghali said 
Clark would not. The government spokesman added that tonight's 
discussion at the presidential palace will concern the UN 
secretary general's report, which was submitted to the Security 
Council on 30 May, and particular emphasis will be placed upon 
Butrus-Ghali's proposals. 
  The spokesman repeated that the Greek Cypriot side's 
position 
remains clear: Discussion of the confidence-building measures 
has ended and we remain committed to the 21 March document. 
Answering a question, the government spokesman stressed that 
our side will not yield to pressure from the United States and 
Britain. 
  Finally, the spokesman said that President Kliridhis will 
leave for Corfu tomorrow morning on board a private plane 
instead of this afternoon as scheduled. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

