<DATE1>  24 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Yeltsin, Churkin Arrive in Corfu for EU Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia's Yeltsin, Churkin Arrive in Corfu for EU Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Views Cooperation With EU </H4>

<F P=102> NC2406063094 Paris AFP in English 0107 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2406063094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Graham Brown] </F>
  [Excerpt] Corfu, Greece, June 24 (AFP) -- Russia takes a 
major step toward integration with Western Europe here Friday 
[24 June] when President Boris Yeltsin signs an historic 
partnership and cooperation agreement with the European Union 
[EU]. 
  The signing ceremony opens a two-day EU summit at which the 
12-nation bloc will also formally sign up new members Austria, 
Finland, Norway and Sweden -- its first enlargement since Spain 
and Portugal entered in 1986. 
  Speaking on his arrival at this Mediterranean island on 
Thursday, Yeltsin thanked the EU for leading the way in "ending 
the discrimination" traditionally accorded to Russia. He said 
Moscow and Brussels were becoming "equal partners." 
  The agreement will greatly increase Russian trade access to 
the EU, open up the prospect of a Russia-EU free trade zone 
after 1998 and provide for wide-ranging political dialogue. 
  It is the latest in a flurry of initiatives to bolster 
reform 
in Russia by binding it more closely to western political, 
economic and military institutions. 
  Two weeks ago Russia signed a cooperation agreement with the 
Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD). 
  On Wednesday it joined the North Atlantic Treaty 
Organisation's partnership for peace programme of military 
cooperation with the countries of the former Soviet bloc. 
  And next month Yeltsin will join in political consultations 
of the G-7 group of industrialised nations -- the United States, 
Japan, Canada, Britain, France, Germany and Italy -- at a summit 
in Naples, Italy. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

