<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Yeltsin, Churkin Arrive in Corfu for EU Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia's Yeltsin, Churkin Arrive in Corfu for EU Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Churkin on Situation in Bosnia </H4>

<F P=102> NC2306185794 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1700 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2306185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mirella Kalostipi] </F>
  [Excerpts] Many senior officials arrived in Corfu today. 
All European Union [EU] leaders are expected to arrive on the 
island by late tonight. French President Francois Mitterrand 
and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl are expected late tonight. 
  Tonight, Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou will host an 
official dinner for the twelve EU leaders, the four new 
partners, and Russian President Boris Yeltsin. 
  The Russian president arrived in Corfu at noon today 
accompanied by Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin 
and Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias. Cypriot President 
Glavkos Kliridhis arrived earlier. Spanish Prime Minister 
Felipe Marquez Gonzalez's plane landed in Ioannis Kapodhistrias 
airport around 1400 today. [passage omitted] 
  Kliridhis said the differences with the Turkish Cypriot side 
have essentially increased and said he hopes that negotiations 
on Cyprus' accession to the EU will begin soon. 
  In a statement, Churkin referred particularly to 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. He said: We will give all sides a last 
chance to reach a peace agreement. If they do not accept these 
proposals, which are extremely detailed and serious, I am afraid 
they will get into serious trouble. The Russian deputy foreign 
minister feels that the parties involved in Bosnia-Herzegovina 
have no political will to reach a peace settlement. In any 
case, an effort will be made in Corfu and a last chance will be 
given to everyone for a peaceful settlement of the Bosnian issue. 
  Churkin described the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina as 
very 
dangerous. He said: What the ministers and the international 
community will attempt to formulate in Corfu and in early July 
is a serious proposal that contains strong elements to motivate 
and to dissuade the three parties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

