<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Greek, Cypriot Goals for EU Corfu Summit Listed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Greek, Cypriot Goals for EU Corfu Summit Listed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2306183194 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2306183194 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The developments on the Cyprus issue and Cyprus' 
accession to the European Union [EU] tonight focus on Corfu, 
where President Glavkos Kliridhis will hold decisive meetings. 
Kliridhis will meet Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou at 
1945 and European Commission President Jacques Delors around 
2030 today. 
  The Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation correspondent in Corfu 
reports that the Greek presidency and the Cypriot Government are 
convinced that tonight's meeting between Papandreou, Delors, and 
Kliridhis will mark a step forward in comparison with the 
previous EU decision to review Cyprus' membership application in 
January 1995. 
  Well-informed sources have told our correspondent that 
Athens 
and Nicosia have set three goals for the Corfu summit. First, 
to specify that official talks on Cyprus' accession to the EU 
will begin in January. Second, if the first goal is not 
achieved, to secure a commitment that the timetable for the 
beginning of accession negotiations will definitely be set next 
January. Third, to see that the EU summit's closing statement 
mentions specifically that the next EU expansion will include 
Cyprus and Malta. 
  Kliridhis will meet British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd 
at 
2330 today. Hurd went to Corfu following his talks on the 
Cyprus issue in New York with the UN secretary general and with 
U.S. officials in Washington. Tonight's meetings come after the 
Cyprus visit by Joe Clark, the UN secretary general's special 
representative for Cyprus. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

