<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Efforts To Elect New EC Commission President Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Efforts To Elect New EC Commission President Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    UK's Major Stands Firm </H4>

<F P=102> LD2306184094 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1738 GMT 23 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306184094 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Geoff Meade in Corfu, PRESS ASSOCIATION News] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister John Major arrived at the Corfu 
Summit tonight refusing to back down in the growing battle over 
who replaces Commission President Jacques Delors. 
  And he hinted that he would be prepared to postpone a 
decision if it avoided putting a candidate unacceptable to 
Britain into the Brussels driving seat. 
  "I think it is important to get the right result -- whether 
that will be here or not I am not sure. Everyone would hope 
so," said the Prime Minister, after flying in for dinner with 
the other EU [European Union] leaders, Russian president Boris 
Yeltsin and the government leaders of Austria, Norway, Finland 
and Sweden, whose countries are due to join the Union next year. 
  Mr. Major gave little away about the hand he will play at 
the 
negotiating table in Corfu tomorrow night. That is when the 
real argument begins over the choice of the new Commission 
president. 
  Mr. Major was asked what was so wrong with Belgian Prime 
Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene, whose candidacy has upset Tory Euro 
sceptics. 
  "I think we had better wait and see what happens in the 
discussion. I have nothing to say about that until we have had 
it." 
  The Prime Minister may even veto Mr. Dehaene's chances in 
what must be a unanimous decision by the 12 leaders. If he did 
so, he would be embroiled in a major row with France and Germany 
who have championed the Belgian's cause. 
  His chief rival for the job, Dutch Prime Minister Ruud 
Lubbers, has refused to withdraw despite the fact that Mr. 
Dehaene already has the support of about half a dozen member 
states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

