<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Efforts To Elect New EC Commission President Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Efforts To Elect New EC Commission President Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Lubbers Reportedly To `Withdraw' </H4>

<F P=102> BR2306142794 Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD in Dutch 23 Jun 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> BR2306142794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "`Lubbers Withdraws'"] </F>
  [Text] Brussels/Bonn -- During yesterday's European 
Peoples' Party (EPP) summit in Brussels, Prime Minister Lubbers 
is said to have agreed to withdraw his candidacy for the 
presidency of the European Commission tomorrow evening. 
  German participants at the EPP summit consultation say that 
Lubbers does not want to risk a tough confrontation at the Corfu 
summit since he does not stand a chance against Belgian Prime 
Minister Dehaene. 
  The EPP summit agreed that as soon as a substantial majority 
is reached in favor of one of the candidates at the European 
Union summit, the one who looks likely to lose will withdraw. 
  In this way a consensus can be reached on who should succeed 
Frenchman Jacques Delors as president of the European Commission. 
  The EPP did not agree to promote any Community 
Christian-Democratic candidates. Before the meeting began, 
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl called on Lubbers and Dehaene to 
embrace "so show that we are all friends." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

