<DOCNO> FBIS4-44002 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu122_h_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-122 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Embassy Staff in Iran Reportedly Accepts Visa Bribes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Embassy Staff in Iran Reportedly Accepts Visa Bribes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306124794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1048 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hamburg (DDP/ADN): German consulate officials in 
Tehran have allegedly accepted bribes to issue visas, according 
to the ARD television magazine program "Panorama." According to 
the report broadcast on Thursday [23 June], genuine visas from 
the embassy are available on the street from middle men for 
prices ranging from 4,000 to 10,000 marks. Contrary to 
regulations, the applicant does not even have to go to the 
embassy to get the entry stamp. The corruptibility of embassy 
staff in Iran and in other countries was on the records of 
German courts and authorities, it was said. 
  A spokesman for the Foreign Ministry said that his 
department 
had no evidence of visa trading of this kind. If the television 
program had suggestions or evidence that proved the involvement 
of the German Embassy in this sort of dealing, then it was their 
duty to inform the Foreign Ministry to enable them to clear up 
the matter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
