<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Schaeuble Terms Scharping Speech `Disappointing' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Schaeuble Terms Scharping Speech `Disappointing' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2306172494 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
23 Jun 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU2306172494 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "fy": "Schaeuble Criticizes Scharping"] </F>
  [Text] Bonn, 22 Jun -- Schaeuble, CDU/CSU [Christian 
Democratic Union/Christian Social Union] Bundestag group 
chairman, described SPD [Social Democratic Party of Germany] 
Chairman Scharping's conference address as disappointing, 
because it lacked concepts and convincing proposals regarding 
solutions to problems. No statement was made on the SPD's goals 
and the speech did not say anything about possible coalitions. 
The question is no longer whether the SPD is tending toward a 
red-green coalition, but whether it will expand such an alliance 
into a popular front by including the PDS [Party of Democratic 
Socialism]. Scharping also failed to provide a clear answer on 
the party's attitude toward the PDS. Instead, the SPD just ran 
everything down: German unification, the economic upturn, and 
the government's foreign policy successes. 
  Scharping's government program contains promises that would 
cost 60 billion German marks to realize, but the candidate for 
chancellor does not mention where the money is to come from. 
Scharping failed to explain how he would combat unemployment 
and modernize the economy. Under him, the SPD has become a 
party that is out of step with reality and keeps its head in the 
sand with regard to the changed political situation in the world 
in a way that would lead Germany into international isolation. 
CSU Land Group Chairman Gloss talked of a desperate attempt on 
the part of Scharping to use emotions to create the impression 
of unity on the part of the SPD. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

