<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   PDS To Compete With SPD, Alliance 90 in Vote </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PDS To Compete With SPD, Alliance 90 in Vote </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2306172094 Berlin NEUES DEUTSCHLAND in German 22 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2306172094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin NEUES DEUTSCHLAND </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by ND: "PDS Wants To Compete With SPD and Alliance </F>
90/Greens"] 
  [Text] Berlin -- The most important goal of the Party of 
Democratic Socialism [PDS] in the Bundestag elections on 16 
October and in the future parliament is the replacement of the 
Kohl government. Despite all the material differences and its 
criticism of the Social Democratic Party of Germany [SPD], PDS 
deputies would "in no event prevent" a change toward an SPD-led 
federal government. This was stressed on Tuesday [21 June] in a 
comprehensive election analysis by election campaign head Andre 
Brie, obtained by NEUES DEUTSCHLAND. 
  The party's main opponents will be right-wing extremist and 
rightist populist groups, Brie affirms. The PDS has "developed" 
its election campaign strategy "not from the viewpoint of 
conflict with the SPD, but proceeding exclusively from its own 
goals and strengths." The PDS competes with the SPD and the 
Alliance 90/Greens for the most consistent representation of the 
interests of the downtrodden of society and the east Germans, 
for the most far-reaching self-representation of the citizens, 
and for the most decisive steps toward a democratic, humanistic, 
and ecologically oriented society. "In contrast to voting for 
the SPD and the Alliance 90/Greens," voting for the PDS "means 
not only voting for a change in government but for political 
change." 
  Brie assesses the results of the European and local 
elections 
of 12 June as a nationwide signal that the PDS is not "on its 
way out," but has political prospects as a socialist party that 
is critical of the system, is "unmistakably to the left of 
Alliance 90/Greens and the SPD," and will again enter the 
Bundestag with more than 5 percent or more than three direct 
mandates. While the PDS is still a zero-point-something party 
in western Germany, in the new laender and in East Berlin its 
prospects for local and land policy "have been secured for the 
foreseeable future. Only the PDS itself could destroy them." 
  Brie says that the PDS failure to get 5 percent in the 
European elections is due to the fact that in Brandenburg, where 
local elections were not held at the same time, the party was 
not able to sufficiently mobilize its potential voters. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

