<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Forces Enter Cyangugu </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Forces Enter Cyangugu </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406102894 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 0900 
GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2406102894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In the opinion of Valery Giscard d'Estaing 
[president of the French Democratic Union], the intervention 
operation in Rwanda poses problems, because it is the 
responsibility of Africa, not Europe, much less France. 
  The French forces of Operation Turquoise in Rwanda have thus 
entered the town of Cyangugu. They have established themselves 
in the Nyarushishi camp. This is where thousands of Tutsi 
civilians fleeing the massacres have taken refuge. No shots 
have been fired, and we have been well received by the people, 
Colonel Andre Chilles said this morning. 
  Two wide-bodied planes carrying more than 100 tonnes of 
medical supplies and equipment left Satolas [Lyon airport] for 
Rwanda this morning. Nicole Guillard reports from Lyon: 
  [Begin Guillard recording] At least 150 tonnes of supplies 
and equipment are going to be transported to Rwanda from 
Satolas. Half of the crates were loaded aboard a wide-bodied 
plane yesterday, and the second will leave late this afternoon. 
They are taking modular operating theater units, medical 
equipment, medicines, and vehicles supplied by Bron military 
college, within the framework of the rapid humanitarian 
intervention air force. This emergency force, incorporated into 
Operation Turquoise, should make possible the rapid 
establishment of two medical units in Zaire, behind the Rwandan 
border. A rapid intervention unit in southeast Rwanda will also 
make it possible to give first aid to the victims of the war, 
thanks to two medical units, a surgical unit, and a dental unit. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

