<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciller Criticizes U.S. Conditions for Military Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ciller Criticizes U.S. Conditions for Military Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2306194094 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2306194094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Excerpts] Prime Minister Tansu Ciller has said that the 
government is trying to find rooted and lasting solutions to the 
country's problems. Addressing the True Path Party's 
parliamentary group, Ciller said that great advances have been 
achieved in the struggle against terror. [passage omitted] 
  Ciller said the Turkish government will continue to support 
a 
just and realistic solution in Cyprus to be attained through 
negotiations. Noting that the Greek Cypriot side has adopted an 
intransigent attitude, Ciller added that the attitude adopted by 
Rauf Denktas, president of the Turkish Republic of Northern 
Cyprus, has proven that the Turkish Cypriot side favors peace. 
  Ciller recalled that the U.S. Congress will be adopting a 
bill stipulating that the arms to be sent or sold to Turkey in 
1995 cannot be employed for domestic security purposes and added: 
  [Begin Ciller recording] I view these developments in the 
U.S. Congress as a great injustice against our country and 
people. The U.S. Senate is actually telling us that U.S. arms 
will not be employed in the struggle against the PKK [Workers 
Party of Kurdistan], which the U.S. Administration has 
explicitly described as a terror organization and whose 
international links are well known. Such a condition is 
tantamount to supporting terror and remaining a spectator to 
attempts to divide Turkey. [end recording] 
  Ciller stated that the attitude of the U.S. Congress can be 
linked to efforts being exerted by a group acting with prejudice 
against Turkey and the Turkish people. She noted that the 
government will do all it can to rectify this injustice, adding 
that a delegation composed of parliamentarians and press 
officials will be sent to the United States to clarify the 
issue. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

