<H3> <TI>   UN Official Continues Talks With Turkish Cypriots </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Official Continues Talks With Turkish Cypriots </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Clark Ends Meetings, Departs </H4>

<F P=102> NC2306160494 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1500 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2306160494 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Joe Clark, the UN secretary general's special 
representative on Cyprus, left Cyprus this afternoon. He met 
President Glavkos Kliridhis last night and Turkish Cypriot 
leader Rauf Denktas today. 
  In a statement, Clark said the agreement that was expected 
on 
the confidence-building measures has not been reached, adding 
that Denktas did not give him the draft agreement on the 
confidence-building measures his side has prepared. He denied 
reports that he conveyed any messages in any form to both sides. 
  Denktas said Clark did not give him any document or letter, 
as he had expected, because the UN secretary general succumbed, 
to use Denktas' expression, to Kliridhis' blackmail that if 
something like this happened he would submit his resignation. 
Denktas added that in his meeting with Clark, he asked why the 
United Nations has not yet prepared a supplementary report on 
the events since 31 May, which demonstrate the goodwill of the 
Turkish Cypriot side. He said that, considering the current 
facts, during his talks in Corfu Kliridhis will cite the UN 
secretary general's 31 May report, which puts the Turkish 
Cypriot side in a bad light, and will accuse it of a lack of 
political goodwill. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

