<H3> <TI>   Russia's Kozyrev Reacts to Poland's NATO Bid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia's Kozyrev Reacts to Poland's NATO Bid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2406120594 Paris LE MONDE in French 24 Jun 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> BR2406120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE MONDE </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Brussels correspondent Jean de la Gueriviere: </F>
"After Several Months of Talks: Russia Finally Signs 
Partnership for Peace Agreement With NATO"] 
  [Excerpts] "This is not Yalta, this is Brussels. There 
cannot be any confusion on this." Thus Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev sought to reassure a journalist from a Baltic 
state whose question reflected a suspicion that the world was 
once again being carved up after Russia's signing of the 
Partnership for Peace [PFP] framework agreement at NATO 
headquarters on Wednesday, 22 June. [passage omitted] 
  During the closing news conference, a Polish journalist 
asked 
Mr. Kozyrev whether Russia would object to Poland joining NATO. 
"As equal partners within NATO, we shall have an equal right to 
say what we think," was all the Russian minister would say, 
mentioning an upcoming meeting with his Polish counterpart to 
discuss the issue. 
  A Lithuanian journalist had an insidious question -- already 
asked by his government -- as to whether small Lithuania could 
ask for a "special relationship" with NATO as part of the PFP, 
in light of the "precedent" created with Russia. NATO Deputy 
Secretary General Sergio Balanzino, who replaced Manfred 
Woerner, still unable to attend due to health problems, did not 
leave him many illusions.... 

</TEXT>

