<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Greek Spokesman on EU Expansion, Meeting Agenda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Greek Spokesman on EU Expansion, Meeting Agenda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2406184294 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2406184294 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Government Spokesman Evangelos Venizelos said: The 
Greek Presidency of the European Council wants to confirm that 
the accession of Cyprus and Malta will take place during the 
next phase of the European Union's [EU] expansion. He added 
that the Republic of Cyprus already meets the nominal criteria 
of the Maastricht Treaty. Mr. Venizelos praised the statement 
of outgoing European Parliament President Egon Klepsch, who 
pointed out the need for Cyprus and Malta to be included in the 
next phase of the EU expansion within a specific time limit. 
  Mr. Venizelos further noted that at the noon meeting of the 
EU summit participants discussed the European election results, 
the French-German initiative to combat racism and xenophobia, 
and the questions pertaining to the so-called Third Pylon -- 
cooperation, internal issues, matters of justice -- that are 
provided for in the Maastricht Treaty. 
  Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou pointed out the phenomenon 
of extreme diaspora of votes to parties that do not belong to 
the European Parliament and the fact that in our country voting 
is compulsory. The prime minister said: The low turnout of the 
European Election should give us reason to think. 
  After the Greek prime minister finished, French President 
Francois Mitterrand took the floor and referred to the 
French-German initiative to combat racism and xenophobia. The 
next speaker was British Prime Minister John Major who referred 
to the need for cooperation between the police authorities of 
the member states. In his address, European Commission 
President Jacques Delors referred to the problem of political 
indifference that was noticed during the European Election. 

</TEXT>

