<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Approve Economic Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leaders Approve Economic Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2406204894 Paris AFP in English 1903 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2406204894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Corfu, Greece, June 24 (AFP) -- European Union [EU] 
leaders meeting here Friday [24 June] agreed the outlines of a 
common economic policy, an essential step if they are to bring 
their economies towards greater union, diplomatic sources said. 
  The talks on price stability, sound public finances and 
labour market flexibility were brief, the main points having 
already been approved at a meeting of the EU member's ministers 
of economy and finance two weeks ago. 
  They had to be approved by the heads of government at the EU 
summit here before being formally adopted by the finance and 
economics ministers at their next meeting. 
  Danish Prime Minister Poul Rasmussen told European leaders 
that the union had to offer a clearer explanation to the public 
indicating that the policy was aimed at fighting unemployment, 
the source said. 
  The convergence criteria set in the Maastricht Treaty on 
European economic and political union set a limit for public 
sector debt of 3 percent of gross domestic product. 
  The criteria have to be met for countries to join a single 
European currency sector due to be agreed at the end of 1997 or 
1999. Few EU member states currently meet the targets. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

