<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Funds Pledged To Close Chernobyl </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Funds Pledged To Close Chernobyl </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2506172694 Paris AFP in English 1409 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2506172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Corfu, Greece, June 25 (AFP) -- The European Union 
[EU] has pledged ECU500 million (575 million dollars) towards 
shutting down Ukraine's Chernobyl nuclear plant, site of the 
world's worst civilian nuclear accident, French President 
Francois Mitterrand said Saturday [25 June]. 
  Speaking after the two-day summit ended here, he said the 
12-member European Union would seek more funding for this 
purpose from other industrialized countries at the Group of 
Seven summit in Naples, Italy, next month. 
  The sum pledged by the EU includes a loan of ECU400 million 
and a gift of ECU100 million. 
  The summiteers agreed during the two-day meeting on the 
necessity of closing down Ukraine's dangerous Chernobyl nuclear 
reactor. Britain, France, Germany and Italy said they would 
press for an agreement on the financing of the shutdown at the 
G7 summit. 
  It is a "very important area," Mitterrand said, adding that 
the EU plan for shutting down Chernobyl included "overall reform 
of the energy sector" in the former Soviet republic of the 
Ukraine. 
  Before the EU summit, France and Germany sent a joint letter 
to their partners stressing the urgency of a quick and total 
shutdown of the entire Chernobyl complex, where the April 1986 
nuclear disaster was caused by an explosion in one of its 
reactors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-44072 </DOCNO>
