<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delors' Extension Proposed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delors' Extension Proposed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2506110994 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2506110994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] According to sources at the 
12 states summit, which ends in Corfu today, the EU state and 
government leaders failed today to agree on the new Commission 
president to succeed Jacques Delors. The same sources also 
noted that German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said that his country, 
which will take over the EU Presidency on 1 July, would like to 
convene an extraordinary summit on 15 July to settle the issue. 
The deadlock in appointing Jacques Delors' successor is caused 
by Britain's opposition to the candidacy of Belgian Prime 
Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene. British Foreign Secretary said that 
the names of other candidates will also be discussed. Dutch 
Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers and British Commissioner on Trade 
Affairs Sir Leon Brittan have withdrawn from the race for the 
Commission presidency. 
  The Greek presidency expressed its displeasure at Britain's 
stand toward the Belgian prime minister's candidacy. Government 
spokesman Evangelos Venizelos said that Greece does not see what 
can change by 15 July when the next extraordinary EU summit will 
convene. He added: The Greek presidency proposed the renewal 
of Jacques Delors term of office. 
  Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation special correspondent Petros 
Petridhis reports that the Greek proposal is being explored and 
that Mr. Venizelos did not give any further details on the 
proposal. At any rate, Mr. Delors' consent will be needed for 
the proposal to be realized. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

