<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delors Declines Fourth Term </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delors Declines Fourth Term </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2506140894 Paris AFP in English 1310 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2506140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Corfu, Greece, June 25 (AFP) -- Outgoing European 
Commission president Jacques Delors on Saturday [25 June] ruled 
out another term as the European Union's top civil servant. 
  Delors, whose third term ends on January 5, had been asked 
by 
Greece to stay on if the 12-nation European Union failed to 
agree on a successor at their summit meeting here. 
  "I would have preferred for the four new members not to have 
to witness the sorry sight of my successor's designation," said 
Delors. 
  He said Europe was in a "serious" crisis. 
  Delors has headed the European Union's Executive Commission 
since 1984. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-44082 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu123cc_94025" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-123 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kohl Suggests July Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kohl Suggests July Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2506103894 Paris AFP in English 0929 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2506103894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Corfu, June 25 (AFP) -- European Union [EU] leaders 
on Saturday [25 June] failed to reach agreement on a new EU 
Commission president and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl proposed 
an emergency summit to decide the matter next month, EU sources 
said. 
  The sources said Kohl had proposed a new summit on July 15. 
  Italian Foreign Minister Antonio Martino said nomination of 
the sole remaining candidate in the race, Belgian Prime Minister 
Jean-Luc Dehaene, had been blocked by Britain. 
  He was speaking on the second day of a two-day EU summit 
which was dominated by a quarrel over a replacement for 
Commission President Jacques Delors, who retires on January 5 as 
the EU's top civil servant. 
  Earlier Saturday, the two other official candidates, Dutch 
Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers and the EU's British trade 
commissioner, Sir Leon Brittan, withdrew their names from the 
race. 
  Martino told journalists that Major was blocking Dehaene's 
nomination on the grounds that it had not been properly handled. 
Expressing support for the British position, he said: "Someone 
should remind us of important principles." 
  All 12 EU leaders must be in agreement for a candidacy to go 
forward to the European Parliament for its approval. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-44083 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu123cc_94026" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-123 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dehaene Notes British Opposition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dehaene Notes British Opposition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2506173194 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1600 
GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2506173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene in </F>
Corfu; date not given--recorded] 
  [Excerpts] The European Union summit in Corfu has ended in 
a major crisis. [passage omitted] Jean-Luc Dehaene made a 
statement after the Corfu summit. He remains a candidate and 
(?takes note of) the British veto. Here is his statement 
recorded by our special correspondent in Corfu: 
  [Begin Dehaene recording] I can see that Great Britain 
opposed my election, not for personal or national reasons, but 
for reasons of principles. In order not to make the work of the 
German presidency more difficult, I will not make any more 
statements about the issue of the presidency until the German 
presidency organizes the special summit. 
  I am disappointed for Europe today. However, I am calm about 
the whole situation. Indeed, I did not put myself up as a 
candidate. At the request of some colleagues, I was and I remain 
available, if necessary, if a consensus is reached. However, I 
am not desperate. As I have said on several occasions over the 
last few days, the results of the European elections in Belgium, 
and especially in Flanders, have reinforced my desire as prime 
minister to achieve all of the government's program. I am 
convinced that it will transpire at the end of my mandate that I 
will get the support of voters to devote myself and commit 
myself to many more years at the service of Belgium and Europe. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

