<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cites Domestic British Politics </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cites Domestic British Politics </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606162394 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1500 
GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2606162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] As you know, Jean-Luc Dehaene returned from Corfu 
having failed in his bid to succeeded Jacques Delors as director 
of the European Commission. One no vote threw everything in the 
air again, the no vote having come from the very isolated 
British. The dossier will doubtless be reopened 15 July at 
another summit in Brussels. Meanwhile Jean-Luc Dehaene is not 
withdrawing. We (?highlight) this comment: As a person, I have 
no problem with John Major. I am not blind to his position in 
Great Britain. I am even sorry for him. These are a few of the 
things said by Jean-Luc Dehaene on television at lunchtime today 
in Mises au Point. Anyway, as far as he is concerned all of 
this is not good for Europe: 
  [Begin recording] [Dehaene] Europe has in fact been blocked 
by Great Britain. That itself is not good for Europe. What is 
worse is that Europe has in fact been blocked for British 
domestic reasons, namely Major's weak position in the 
Conservative Party. He is under pressure from the Eurosceptics. 
There has been a press campaign against me which he apparently 
cannot resist, so he chose to try to strengthen his domestic 
position--and it is not clear that will be the right path in the 
long run--rather than to play the European game and join the 
consensus. So in relation to the Twelve, and in particular to 
the Eleven who reached a consensus on my candidacy, this creates 
a problem, because we are not going to put ourselves in a 
situation where one says: no, and then all the others say: oh, 
all right, we give in and we'll go and look for someone else. 
  I am not speaking of the parliament, because when I see some 
of the initial reactions in the European Parliament, I say to 
myself that the European Council must pay great attention to 
what it does, because then there could be a return to form as 
far as parliament is concerned. [as heard] [end recording] 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

