<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balladur, Berlusconi Discuss Successor, Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Balladur, Berlusconi Discuss Successor, Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2406175794 Paris AFP in English 1641 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2406175794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Corfu, Greece, June 24 (AFP) -- French Prime 
Minister Edouard Balladur had his first meeting here Friday [24 
June] with Italy's new premier, Silvio Berlusconi. 
  French diplomats said the meeting had "gone well." It dealt 
with the contest to name a successor to European Commission 
president Jacques Delors, and with France's military 
intervention in Rwanda. 
  They said Balladur had been "agreeably surprised" by the 
performance of the Italian Government formed by Berlusconi in 
April, but shared general concern at the presence in his 
coalition cabinet of five neofascist members. 
  Berlusconi called the meeting "very cordial," and said he 
had 
raised the possibility of another meeting between the two men. 
  Earlier on the sidelines of the summit, Berlusconi had talks 
with British Prime Minister John Major. The two men agreed to 
meet again soon, but did not announce a date. 

</TEXT>

