<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Major, Berlusconi Agree to Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Major, Berlusconi Agree to Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2406151294 Paris AFP in English 1304 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2406151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Corfu, Greece, June 24 (AFP) -- Britain and Italy 
on Friday [24 June] agreed to hold an Anglo-Italian summit 
meeting, British officials said after the first meeting between 
the two countries' leaders since Italian elections in March 
brought neofascists into the government. 
  British Prime Minister John Major and Italian Prime Minister 
Silvio Berlusconi agreed in principle to hold the Anglo-Italian 
summit, though the date and place were not yet decided, British 
officials said. 
  The Major-Berlusconi meeting, which took place on the 
sidelines of the 51st European Union [EU] summit here, lasted 75 
minutes and centred on the agenda for the meeting of EU leaders, 
British officials said. 
  Almost immediately after Berlusconi's nomination as the new 
Italian prime minister in April, British Foreign Secretary 
Douglas Hurd invited him to London for an Anglo-Italian summit. 
  Berlusconi ruffled British feathers by instead making his 
first foreign outing last week to Bonn, visiting German 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl. 
  Earlier in June he also met US President Bill Clinton when 
the US head of state was in Rome on a week-long European tour to 
commemorate the 50th anniversary of the liberation of Rome and 
the D-Day landings. 
  The British and Italian leaders also discussed their 
position 
on the succession to Jacques Delors as European Commission 
president, the officials said, but declined further details. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

