<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Officials, Others Comment on Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Officials, Others Comment on Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Details of Medical Unit </H4>

<F P=102> LD2506160694 Paris Radio France International in French 1230 
GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2506160694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The French Operation Turquoise in Rwanda is 
primarily a humanitarian operation. In the wake of soldiers 
dispatched to Bukavu, Zaire, to enter the western part of 
Rwanda, a full medical and surgical infrastructure is ready to 
be set up. Jean-Noel Ferre, a general with the French Army 
Medical Corps, outlined the technical details of the operation 
to Jean-Pierre Boris: 
  [Begin recording] [Ferre] This infrastructure is made up of 
a 
surgical team, with two surgeons and an anaesthetist, two 
medical teams including two doctors each, a 50-bed hospital 
section, a laboratory unit and an X-ray unit. 
  [Boris] What about the surgical unit? 
  [Ferre] The surgical unit is a simple surgical unit which 
can 
only carry out emergency surgery. It is manned by three 
doctors, two surgeons and an anaesthetist, six fully qualified 
nurses, and three soldiers. 
  This gives you a broad picture of the infrastructure we are 
setting up: On one hand a surgical unit for the troops, in case 
of fighting; and on the other hand a medical unit that includes 
a surgical team and two medical teams -- with laboratory and 
X-ray sections -- to cater to the refugees. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

