<H3> <TI>   Government Officials, Others Comment on Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Officials, Others Comment on Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Mitterrand on International Support </H4>

<F P=102> LD2506160394 Paris Radio France International in French 1230 
GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2506160394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Mitterrand spoke from Corfu, where he is 
attending the EU [European Union] summit, about the French 
intervention in Rwanda. Journalists asked the president if 
France had received enough backing from the international 
community. 
  [Begin Mitterrand recording] Enough, yes. There is a major 
difference between saying nothing and expressing support. When 
we asked the question, they all told us that they supported the 
French initiative. Now, you will ask me, are they supporting us 
by dispatching soldiers? Some will answer a call for logistical 
support, others are perhaps getting ready to supply troops, 
others, it depends. This is not only specific to the Twelve, 
proposals also came from Africa and from a few other countries. 
  First of all, the deployment of equipment and troops took 
place in excellent conditions; it was very well organized. The 
move into Rwandan territory often took place with the very warm 
agreement of the people, if I can trust what you journalists are 
writing as well as our own information. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

