<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Magdeburg (DDP/ADN) -- Lothar Bisky, leader of the 
Party of Democratic Socialism [PDS], described his party's 
performance in the Saxony Anhalt state elections as another step 
by the PDS in the direction of the Bundestag. Commenting on the 
most recent computer predictions, which show the Socialist Unity 
Party's successor party as the third-strongest party with 18 
percent of the vote, Bisky told journalists that Saxony Anhalt 
shows that "people in the east want us." Despite really massive 
threats in recent weeks, the voters did not allow themselves to 
be confused, he said, adding that this is a good thing and gives 
him confidence for the federal elections. The PDS is aiming for 
at least three first-past-the-post seats, and thus entry into 
the federal parliament, Bisky said. 

