<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Kliridhis, Others Comment on EU Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Kliridhis, Others Comment on EU Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Greek Foreign Ministry Comments </H4>

<F P=102> NC2506204294 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2506204294 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Responding to a question by the Cyprus Broadcasting 
Corporation correspondent, Greek Foreign Ministry Secretary 
General Ioannis Kranidhiotis said the Greek Presidency's 
proposal was for negotiations to begin and conclude before the 
1996 intergovernment conference, and then Cyprus would join the 
European Union [EU] after the conference. 
  Kranidhiotis said the proposal was removed during the 
discussion. Objections were mainly raised by France, which wants 
the institutional operational framework to be set first; 
Germany, which links the issue with Turkey; and Britain, which 
links the issue with progress in the Cyprus issue. The 
secretary general added that what we have achieved is that the 
next expansion phase will certainly include Cyprus and Malta. 
He said what is more important is that Cyprus' accession is no 
longer linked to developments in the Cyprus issue. He concluded 
that the issue of beginning accession negotiations will be 
raised many times before 1996 in order to achieve a commitment 
for the beginning of negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

