<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgium To Provide Hospital Team for Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Belgium To Provide Hospital Team for Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2706164494 Paris AFP in English 1629 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2706164494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, June 27 (AFP) -- France has asked Belgium 
to supply medical aid such as emergency hospital units for its 
military intervention in Rwanda, the Ministry of Defence said 
Monday [27 June]. 
  Belgium has agreed to transport the equipment as long as 
French soldiers "ensure the safety of any surgeons sent to 
Rwanda," a spokesman said. Belgium also wanted to see the 
French security zone extended, "so our team can work in the best 
possible conditions." 
  France was interested in the type of Belgian unit already 
used in Somalia, complete with medical supplies and personnel, 
which can carry out operations in any situation, he said. The 
location of the unit has not been established. 
  Two field hospitals have already been set up at French base 
camps in nearby Zaire for Operation Turquoise, launched last 
Thursday, described by Paris as a humanitarian bid to stop 
ethnic killings in the Rwandan civil war. 

</TEXT>

