<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Replaces Two Inspectors in North Korea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA Replaces Two Inspectors in North Korea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2706132794 Paris AFP in English 1221 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2706132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, June 27 (AFP) -- Two inspectors from the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) are on their way to 
North Korea to replace their two colleagues who have been 
working at the contentious Yongbyon plant for several weeks, an 
IAEA spokesman said Monday [27 June]. 
  Hans-Friedrich Meyer said the two new inspectors, who should 
arrive in Pyongyang Tuesday, will continue supervision of the 
experimental nuclear reactor at Yongbyon, 90 kilometres (56 
miles) north of the capital. 
  North Korea created a crisis earlier this month by refusing 
to allow international supervision to check whether material has 
been diverted from the Yongbyon complex for military use. 
  One of the two inspectors currently in Korea will leave 
Tuesday and the other will leave at the end of the week after 
briefing his two colleagues, Meyer said. 
  "It is essential for us that two inspectors remain on the 
spot," Meyer stressed, adding that the two officials obtained 
visas without any trouble. 
  The duration of the inspectors' visit has not been fixed, 
but 
an "old rule" of the atomic watchdog fixes inspectors' tours of 
duty at three weeks. 
  Bilateral talks between the United States and North Korea 
are 
scheduled to be held in Geneva, Switzerland, on July 8. 
  North Korea paved the way for the new talks by agreeing not 
to refuel the reactor, and not to reprocess nuclear fuel -- to 
make the plutonium needed to manufacture atomic weapons -- and 
to allow the IAEA inspectors to remain in North Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

