<H3> <TI>   Turkish, Russian, U.S., Kazakh Technical Specialists Meet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Turkish, Russian, U.S., Kazakh Technical Specialists Meet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2506102994 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1000 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2506102994 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, June 25 (A.A) -- Technical specialists from 
Turkey, Russia, the United States, and Kazakhstan concluded 
their meetings in Ankara, officials said on Saturday [25 June]. 
  BOTAS [Pipeline and Petroleum Transport Corporation] 
Director 
General Hayrettin Uzun told AA reporter that as the Azeri 
officials could not attend the meeting no concrete developments 
had been possible but a sub-committee would be set up to make 
further technical researches. 
  The "the pipe-line working group" whose meeting lasted two 
days was to discuss the route of a proposed Azeri, Russian, and 
Kazakhstan oil pipeline that will reach Europe. 
  The United States which was represented by Chevron company 
which will produce and market the oil participated as third 
country, while Turkish and Russian delegations constituted the 
main sides. 
  Officials from Foreign Ministry, Foreign Trade Under 
Secretariat, energy and natural resources, and BOTAS company 
also took part in the Turkish delegation. 

</TEXT>

