<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cetin Discusses EU With French Ministry Official </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cetin Discusses EU With French Ministry Official </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2806120294 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 0945 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2806120294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, June 28 (A.A.) -- Foreign Minister Hikmet 
Cetin met French Foreign Ministry Undersecretary Bertrand 
Dufourcq, who is currently in Ankara for political talks between 
Turkey and France, it was reported on Monday [27 June]. 
  Dufourcq said after the meeting that France will do its best 
to improve relations between Turkey and the European Union [EU] 
and try to create concrete conditions. Dufourcq also said Greek 
Cypriots have the right to apply for EU membership. "However, 
expanding the Union will be discussed after a process of 
reviewing several institutions in the Union," he said. Asked if 
France will attend a tripartite meeting that is scheduled to be 
held between Turkey, Germany, and Britain's attendance, Dufourcq 
said, "We have been invited and we want to participate in the 
meeting." 
  Meanwhile, Foreign Ministry officials briefing on a meeting 
between Dufourcq and Foreign Ministry Undersecretary Ozdem 
Sanberk said bilateral relations were discussed. 
  It was also reported that the two undersecretaries discussed 
about privatization and increasing French investments in Turkey 
was also in the meeting agenda. 
  Foreign Ministry officials said France and the Union did not 
have the attitude to accept Greek-Cypriots to the Union. 
Officials said Turkey conveyed the French side that Greek 
Cypriot side, who is already making use of the existing 
situation, would exploit the membership if the Union accepted 
the Greek Cypriots to the Union. 

</TEXT>

