<H3> <TI>   Martens Considered `Hot Tip' for EC Commission Post </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Martens Considered `Hot Tip' for EC Commission Post </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2706151594 Berlin DIE WELT in German 27 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2706151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ulrich Rosenbaum: "British Veto Triggers Severe </F>
Crisis in EU"] 
  [Excerpts] Bonn -- Following the failed attempt to appoint 
a new European Commission president at the summit on the Greek 
island of Corfu due to the British Government's stubbornness, 
government circles in Bonn are preparing to have to find a 
completely new candidate to succeed outgoing Jacques Delors. 
[passage omitted] 
  Bonn says that Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl wants to stick 
to the candidate of his choice for the time being; but as yet, 
Kohl has not found a solution for the special summit either. 
Bonn circles regard former Belgian Prime Minister Wifried 
Martens as a "hot tip." The 58-year-old Flemish Christian 
Democrat is chairman of the European People's Party. 
  Members of the delegation accompanying Kohl to the Corfu 
summit say that Major probably rejected Dehaene mainly because 
he fears he might promote European integration too much for 
Britain's liking. Following the devastating defeat Major's 
Conservative Party suffered in the European elections, the prime 
minister's statement that he will not change his mind over the 
next four weeks is considered credible. Kohl, therefore, does 
not want to provoke the British Government, but rather to try to 
have intensive talks with London in order to find a joint 
solution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

